Title: Binary Search Tree

Content.Text:
A binary tree is a data structure in which each node has at most two children, referred to as the left child and the right child.
Children: 0, 1, or 2 children

Diagrams.Description: Valid Binary Tree: A tree with one root and two children.
Diagrams.Interpretation: This represents a correct structure of a binary tree.

Diagrams.Description: Invalid Binary Tree: A tree with one root and three children.
Diagrams.Interpretation: This represents an incorrect structure of a binary tree.

Content.Text:
Process:
1. Compare the value to be inserted (e.g., 9) with the root node (e.g., 10).
   - If 9 < 10, move to the left child.
   - If 9 > 10, move to the right child.
2. Continue this process until the correct position is found.
3. Insert the value at the correct position.

Diagrams.Description: Example of inserting 9 into a binary tree with root 10 and left child 4.
Diagrams.Interpretation: The value 9 is inserted as the right child of 4.

General form: \(|f(n)| \leq C \cdot g(n)\)
